The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                 
	Colombo: Sri Lanka middle-order batsman Thilan Samaraweera was Thursday discharged from hospital, two weeks after suffering a bullet injury in the terror attack in Lahore.    
	Samaraweera was treated at the Nawaloka hospital where a bullet from his left leg was removed after the Sri Lanka team returned home from Lahore.        
	Mohali: The Punjab Cricket Association Thursday came under the income tax department scanner. A team of IT sleuths swooped down on phase IX of the PCA stadium in Mohali at around 1pm and began search operations after prohibiting entry and exit from the place. The operation was continuing till reports last came in and were expected to continue overnight.         
	Dhaka: The Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) has given its players and management a 30 per cent pay rise six months after the national team lost more than a dozen men to the rebel Indian Cricket League (ICL), a statement said Thursday.        
	Bangkok: Rohan Bopanna partnered Pakistans Aisam-Ul-Haq Qureshi to reach the doubles semi-finals in the $50,000 Bangkok Open ATP Challenger tennis tournament here Thursday.        
	Rome: AC Milan chief executive Adriano Galliani has called for a salary cap in soccer to cut costs as the sport deals with the global economic crisis.        
	Calcutta: The Calcutta Ladies Golf Club is all set to start a junior golf academy  the Protouch Golf Academy  at its Maidan tent from April 1. Interested students will be under the tutelage of Indrajit Bhalotia and other prominent coaches.        
	Jaipur: Rashid Khan opened up a two-stroke lead with his second successive round of one-under 69 at the LG Rambagh Golf Club Open Amateur golf tournament here Thursday.        
	Paris: Triple Olympic gold medallist Usain Bolt has agreed to run in the Golden League track meet in Paris this summer for his first competitive appearance in France.     
	The Jamaican sprinter will run in either the 100 or 200 metres at the July 17 meet, organisers said Thursday.        
	Berlin: The International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) will decide this week whether a revealing book by British sprinter Dwain Chambers, banned in the past for doping, has brought the sport into disrepute. The IAAF council is meeting on March 21-22 in Berlin.    
